## C# CODE STYLE

- Use C# 9+ features where Unity version allows (records, pattern matching).
- Prefer readonly fields and immutable data models for metrics results.
- Use sealed on experiment classes unless explicitly designed for inheritance.
- Async/await is allowed in ExperimentRunner for frame-delayed operations.
  Use UniTask if added to the project; otherwise use IEnumerator coroutines.
- Do not use Resources.Load<>() — use direct references or Addressables.
- Avoid LINQ in hot paths (per-frame Update, metric sampling). It allocates.
- Always use string.IsNullOrEmpty() over == null on strings.
- XML documentation is required on all public interfaces and public methods.

---

## UNITY-SPECIFIC RULES

- Never call Physics, Renderer, or Quality API changes from a non-main thread.
- XRSettings changes must happen on the main thread; schedule via dispatcher if async.
- Profile with Unity Profiler Recorder API (ProfilerRecorder), not Time.deltaTime alone.
  Time.deltaTime measures frame time including vsync stall — not pure CPU cost.
- GPU metrics require ProfilerRecorder with "GPU Frame Time" stat name.
- For Quest builds: IL2CPP + ARM64 only. Never build with Mono for device profiling.
- Avoid Camera.main in hot paths — cache it on Awake.
- Use [SerializeField] over public fields on MonoBehaviours.
- Tag Bootstrap and persistent managers with [DefaultExecutionOrder(-100)].

